,"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of shortness of breath and right-sided chest pain. The pain increases with inspiration and is non-radiating. She has been bed-bound and on nasogastric tube feeding since suffering an ischaemic stroke three weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 118/min, blood pressure 82/54 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 86% on room air, and temperature 37.7\u00b0C. Her BMI is 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Cardiovascular examination reveals dual heart sounds with no murmurs. Respiratory examination shows equal air entry to both lungs. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia with non-specific ST changes. Investigations reveal a slightly elevated troponin. A chest X-ray result is currently pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumothorax","Pneumonia","Pulmonary embolism","Pericarditis","Gastritis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E. The sudden onset of dyspnoea and pleuritic chest pain in a patient with significant risk factors (obesity and recent immobilisation due to stroke) strongly suggests this diagnosis. The tachycardia, hypotension, and hypoxia further support this conclusion. The ECG findings of sinus tachycardia and non-specific ST changes are also compatible with pulmonary embolism. It\u0027s worth noting that while the troponin is slightly elevated, this can occur in pulmonary embolism due to right ventricular strain and does not necessarily indicate myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E can cause sudden onset of dyspnoea and pleuritic chest pain. However, it typically presents with unilateral decreased breath sounds and hyperresonance to percussion, which are not described in this case. Additionally, the patient\u0027s risk factors and the presence of hypotension are more suggestive of pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E could cause dyspnea, tachycardia, and pleuritic chest pain. However, the acute onset, lack of productive cough, and the presence of significant risk factors for thromboembolism make pulmonary embolism more likely in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause chest pain that worsens with inspiration, but it typically doesn\u0027t cause such significant hypoxia or hypotension. Additionally, a pericardial friction rub would often be audible on examination, which is not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes epigastric pain or discomfort rather than right-sided chest pain. It would not explain the patient\u0027s dyspnoea, hypoxia, or hypotension. While patients on nasogastric tube feeding can develop gastritis, the overall clinical picture is much more consistent with pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In a patient who presents acutely with chest pain and dyspnoea, with risk factors such as obesity and recent immobilisation, pulmonary embolism must be considered and ruled out.","Pulmonary embolism can present with pleuritic chest pain, tachycardia, hypotension, and hypoxia.","ECG findings in pulmonary embolism may include sinus tachycardia and non-specific ST changes."],"references":["Freund Y, Cohen-Aubart F, Bloom B. Acute Pulmonary Embolism: A Review. JAMA. 2022;328(13):1336\u20131345. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/2796942","Kahn SR, de Wit K. Pulmonary Embolism. N Engl J Med. 2022 Jul 7;387(1):45-57. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp2116489"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96349"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11588"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96349"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T19:16:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T19:17:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4215"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{